{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"660"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/660"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.67,0.1,0.01,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114870"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/660"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114870"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of rapid onset of right lower abdominal pain associated with nausea, vomiting, and light-headedness. She states the pain is constant and is worst when moving or going over bumps in the car. Her last menstrual period was five weeks ago. She recently started a new sexual relationship and her partner uses condoms. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right lower quadrant with localised guarding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perforated appendicitis","Ruptured ectopic pregnancy","Ruptured ovarian cyst","Salpingitis","Ovarian torsion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms highly suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eruptured ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E. The sudden onset of lower abdominal pain in a woman of reproductive age, coupled with tachycardia and hypotension, should raise immediate concern for this diagnosis. The patient\u0027s last menstrual period was five weeks ago, which is consistent with the typical timing for presentation of an ectopic pregnancy. Whilst this patient reports using condoms, they have a significant failure rate and she may not have perfect use. Considering that the clinical history and signs point to ruptured ectopic pregnancy as the most likely diagnosis, a vague reference to using condoms should not be the deciding factor in excluding this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforated appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E could present with right lower quadrant pain, but typically has a more gradual onset with preceding symptoms such as anorexia, fever, and generalised abdominal pain before localising to the right iliac fossa. The sudden onset and haemodynamic instability in this case would be quite unusual for appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eruptured ovarian cyst\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute lower abdominal pain and can cause haemodynamic instability if there is significant intraperitoneal bleeding. However, it would not typically be associated with a missed period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalpingitis\u003C/strong\u003E, or pelvic inflammatory disease, typically presents with a more gradual onset of bilateral lower abdominal pain, often accompanied by fever and vaginal discharge. The acute presentation and haemodynamic instability in this case are not typical for salpingitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian torsion\u003C/strong\u003E can present with sudden onset lower abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. While it remains a possibility, it is less common than ruptured ectopic pregnancy and would not typically cause such significant haemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in this scenario is that every woman of reproductive age presenting with abdominal pain should be considered pregnant until proven otherwise. The combination of missed period, acute lower abdominal pain, and haemodynamic instability (tachycardia and hypotension) strongly suggests a ruptured ectopic pregnancy. Immediate assessment with a pregnancy test and urgent ultrasound would be indicated, along with preparation for possible emergency surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a young woman with sudden onset of lower abdominal pain, a ruptured ectopic pregnancy should always be considered.","Tachycardia and hypotension in a woman of reproductive age with abdominal pain are concerning for ruptured ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Elson CJ, Salim R, Potdar N, Chetty M, Ross JA, Kirk EJ on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy. BJOG 2016;.123:e15\u2013e55. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27813249/","Bleeding \u0026 Pain in Early Pregnancy: Ectopic Pregnancy, Miscarriage \u0026 PUL. In: South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline [online]. Available at: \u00a0https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/fead0f004ee4554cb7ecbfd150ce4f37/Bleeding+and+Pain+in+Early+Pregnancy_PPG_v1_1.pdf","Huang C, Hong\u00a0MK, Ding DC. A review of ovary torsion.\u00a0Ci Ji Yi Xue Za Zhi. 2017;29(3):143-147. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28974907/","Di Saverio, S., Podda, M., De Simone, B.\u00a0et al.\u00a0Diagnosis and treatment of acute appendicitis: 2020 update of the WSES Jerusalem guidelines.\u00a0World J Emerg Surg\u00a015,\u00a027 (2020). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32295644/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"660"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T11:57:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T11:58:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"660"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114870"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"de